<article xml:id="session1wks" label="1234"> <!-- Change label to a random string of numbers for each worksheet. The label shows up in the url of the website and keeps students from searching for other worksheets -->
  <title>MATH 140 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
     For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <worksheet>
    <title> Session #1 (Sections 1.1-1.2)</title>
    <p>
      Directions:
    </p>
    
    <paragraphs> <!--   %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%   SECTION 1  %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%    -->
      <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>

      <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #1 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            	Given the matrices below, determine if the following computations are possible. If the computations are possible, find the resulting matrix by hand (i.e., do the math without a calculator), then check your answer using your calculator. If the computation is not possible, state why. 
          </p>
          
            <m>
            A = \begin{bmatrix}
            2 &amp; -1 &amp; 4 \\
            0 &amp; 3 &amp; 5
            \end{bmatrix},
            \;
            B = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 &amp; 2 &amp; -3 \\
            4 &amp; -1 &amp; 0
            \end{bmatrix},
            \;
            E = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 &amp; 2 &amp; -3 \\
            6 &amp; 0 &amp; -4\\
            7 &amp; 18 &amp; 12
            \end{bmatrix},
            \;
            H = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 &amp; -2 \\
            0&amp; 4 \\
            -2 &amp; 3
            \end{bmatrix}
            </m>

           <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                <m> A + 2B </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                 <m> 3A-H </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>4B-H^T </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                 <m> 2BH </m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #2 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            	Find a matrix F such that the following matrix equation is true.
          </p>
          
            <m>
              \begin{bmatrix}
              1 &amp; 2 &amp; -3 \\
              6 &amp; 0 &amp; -4 \\
              7 &amp; 18 &amp; 12
              \end{bmatrix}
              - F =
              \begin{bmatrix}
              0 &amp; -10 &amp; 30 \\
              2 &amp; 5 &amp; -6 \\
              12 &amp; -3 &amp; 9
              \end{bmatrix}
            </m> 
               
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #3 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> that make the matrix equation below true. 
          </p>
          
            <m>
              \begin{bmatrix}
              x &amp; 2 \\
               3 &amp; y \\
              5 &amp; -1 
              \end{bmatrix}
              +
              \begin{bmatrix}
              1 &amp; -2 \\
               0 &amp; 4\\
              -2 &amp; 3 
              \end{bmatrix}
              =
              \begin{bmatrix}
              4 &amp; 0\\ 
              3 &amp; 10 \\
              3 &amp; 2 
              \end{bmatrix}
              </m>

        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #4 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given matrices  
            <m>
              K=\begin{bmatrix}
              1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3\\
              4 &amp; x &amp; 6
              \end{bmatrix}
            </m>
            and 
             <m>
              L=\begin{bmatrix}
              y &amp; 8 &amp; 9\\
              0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2
              \end{bmatrix}
            </m>,
          </p>
           <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                Find <m> (K+L)^T. </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                 Find <m> K^T + L^T. </m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  True or False: <m>(K+L)^T = K^T +L^T</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
            

        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </paragraphs>

    <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #5 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            5)	Laura is planning to buy sugar, flour, milk, and eggs for her bakery business. The prices of these items in three neighborhood supermarkets are shown in the table below. 
            
<table>
  <tabular>
    <row>
      <cell></cell>
      <cell>Sugar (5-lb bag )</cell>
      <cell>Flour (5-lb bag )</cell>
      <cell>Milk (1-gal carton )</cell>
      <cell>Eggs (1-dozen carton )</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell>Supermarket 1</cell>
      <cell>$3.29</cell>
      <cell>$3.99</cell>
      <cell>$2.79</cell>
      <cell>$2.99</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell>Supermarket 2</cell>
      <cell>$2.89</cell>
      <cell>$2.99</cell>
      <cell>$2.99</cell>
      <cell>$3.49</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell>Supermarket 3</cell>
      <cell>$3.49</cell>
      <cell>$2.74</cell>
      <cell>$3.09</cell>
      <cell>$2.89</cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</table>

          </p>
           <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                Write a 3×4 matrix A to represent the prices of the four items in the three supermarkets.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                 For the first week Laura plans to buy three 5-lb bags of sugar, six 5-lb bags of flour, four 1-gal cartons of milk, and four 1-dozen carton of eggs. Write a 4×1 matrix B to represent the quantities of each item that Laura plans to purchase for the first week.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  	For the second week Laura plans to buy two 5-lb bags of sugar, three 5-lb bags of flour, five 1-gal cartons of milk, and two 1-dozen carton of eggs. Write a 4×1 matrix C to represent the quantities of each item that Laura plans to purchase for the second week.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  	Find B+C and interpret the meaning of the matrix.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  	If T=A(B+C) , what does matrix T represent?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  	Use your calculator to find matrix T and then determine which supermarket Laura should buy the items from to minimize her cost? (Assuming she only shops at one supermarket)
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
            

        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #6 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose G = <m>\begin{bmatrix}x &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; y\end{bmatrix}</m>, H = <m>\begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ -1 &amp; 4\end{bmatrix}</m>, and GH = <m>\begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 8 \\ 0 &amp; 12\end{bmatrix}</m>. Find the values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
          </p>
          
            
               
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1in"><!-- #7 -->
        <statement>
          <p>
           	A company tracks sales of three products (A,B, and D ) across four regions ( R1,R2,R3, and R4 ). Matrix S below represents the amount of each product sold in each region.
          </p>
        
<m>S=</m><table>
  <tabular>
    <row>
      <cell></cell>
      <cell>R1</cell>
      <cell>R2</cell>
      <cell>R3</cell>
      <cell>R4</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell>Product A</cell>
      <cell>100</cell>
      <cell>200</cell>
      <cell>150</cell>
      <cell>175</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell>Product B</cell>
      <cell>80</cell>
      <cell>120</cell>
      <cell>90</cell>
      <cell>110</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell>Product D</cell>
      <cell>60</cell>
      <cell>70</cell>
      <cell>65</cell>
      <cell>85</cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</table>


           <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                <p>
                If the prices of Product A,B, and D are $5, $10, and $8 respectively, create a 1×3 matrix C that represents the cost of each product.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                Write an equation using matrices S and C that represents the revenue matrix R.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  	Find the revenue matrix R and interpret the meaning of <m>r_13</m> .
                </p>
              </li> 
            </ol>     
               
        </statement>
      </exercise>


